			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Chapter 12- Memories
<br />

<br />
Commander Sterling sat uncomfortably in the cold steel chair of whatever transport ship was taking him to meet Mazuko aboard Space Station Lancer. All around him men and women from all over Azguardian controlled space sat in various stages of exhaustion. It had been a long flight, four days at least. Four days trapped in a tin can floating through the vast darkness of space. Their lives guaranteed by engines and air processing systems built by the lowest bidder. Capitalism had reached the entire known galaxy; supposedly it was the greatest contribution Human Kind had made to the universe. Max laughed to himself at that thought. Greatest contribution to the universe, it had only been a few hundred years and already the Great War had been forgotten. "Greatest contribution of man...heh...the greatest contribution of man was life itself!" Max thought aloud. Realizing he had said that aloud he leaned back down in his chair and sighed picking up a tourist magazine from the seat beside him. Inside was hundreds of pictures of Space Station Lancer it was truly a marvelous looking station. Especially when one takes into consideration the sheer number of battles he knew it had been through.
<br />
Max tried to think back to when he first enlisted in the service, his family thought him a fool all but Mallory. Ah lovely Mallory, she was the only thing that had kept him from enlisting. She was the one woman that held his heart, and she held it tightly, for a little while. He loved her, and she knew it, but he would never admit it. She was everything to him; as long as he had her he had no reason to travel the galaxy with the mighty Azguardian battle fleets. But she kept telling him he would be the greatest pilot ever known, that he should follow his dreams wherever they may take him. And so he did.
<br />
He followed a dream that led him to where he was today, one of the most trusted Commanders in all of the Azguardian battle fleets. Max took a deep breath, regretting having left Mallory back on Velious-14. Had he made the right choice? He would never know.
<br />
Max pulled an old letter from his breast pocket, a letter that he had received shortly after he had enlisted. The letter was from his father telling him how things were going on the farm and what the weather was like. He started to read it for what must have been the thousandth time. His eyes watered every time he came to the end where his mother had penned the seven most painful lines he had ever, this time was no different.
<br />

<br />
"Max, if your reading this, it means you are alive and well. I miss you so, I wish you had not gone, but alas you followed your dreams. I hope you are doing well. Everything is ok here, your father is overworking as usual and we have a large crop this year. Although, it pains me to tell you this because I know she has not the heart to tell you herself. Yes, it is about Mallory. I'm sorry my son but she has taken on a husband, Mark Stahl. They have a child due in a few weeks. I just thought you'd want to know. Your father and I love you Max. Take Care.
<br />
Mother"
<br />

<br />
Max wiped his eyes with his fingers struggling to remember the night he got the letter. He had just gotten back from a skirmish with an Imperial Scourge fleet of Doomstar's that they had obliterated. They had started a devastating war for many clusters that day. His only reason for living and fighting was to protect his home planet and the hope that he would return to Mallory's arms again. His hopes and dreams were shattered in a single night. His heart was ripped out, stepped on, ground up, and shoved back into his chest when he learned of Mallory's marriage to Mark Stahl. He barely ate enough to stay alive, his health declined and his weight dropped weekly. Ultimately he wound up in the infirmary. Stripped of his pilot status having it taken away by his Commanding officer, he fell into a deep depression. That was when he met Mazuko.
<br />
Mazuko at that time was an up and coming Commander in the Azguardian military. A man whom many thought would never become more than a deck hand. Max remembered when Mazuko first approached him as he did many of the other patients in the infirmary. All Mazuko did was shake his hand and sat down for a few minutes sharing a few words of encouragement with him.
<br />
Max shook his head chuckled to himself the incident reminding him of politicians and their desperate struggle to win the hearts of their constituents.
<br />
Normally Max would have dismissed the whole event as just another Commander looking for publicity. However Mazuko had said something to him that day he hadn't said to any of the other men in the infirmary. He had said that he was being given his own fleet and that he needed a top notch Commander to help lead the fleet to victory. He had offered Max a second chance and jumped at that opportunity.
<br />
The next morning he had head out with a brand new take on life. A life given to him by a man no one believed in, a man he would follow into the depths of hell, a man he would call brother.
<br />

<br />
Max awoke as the transport ship began the descent to the docking bay of Lancer Station apparently he had nodded off. Wiping the sleep out of his eyes the rest of the passengers began to file out of the transport and onto the landing terminal. He stood up and stretched before following them shortly there after. He retrieved his firearm from the arms locker at the head of the transport ship as he stepped out onto the terminal.
<br />
Max took a look at his watch. It was 18:00 and he didn't have to meet with Mazuko until 22:00. He had more than enough time to grab something to eat, and he was hungry. So he headed to the commercial section of the station looking for a bar.
<br />
After walking around for about an hour Max made his way into a bar called Skullsplitters. He made his way past some odd looking customers, some human, some not, even though most of the humans didn't look so human anymore. Everyone looked at him as if he were the plague. They looked upon him as if he were something to be stepped on, killed, and cast aside.
<br />
Cautiously he took a seat at the bar as the bartender; a short stout man slithered over to him.
<br />
"What can I get for you bub?" said the bartender.
<br />
"Just give me a burger and a glass of water."
<br />
"It'll be a few minutes," said the tender as he took the towel from his shoulder and wiped his greasy hands off leaving a yellowed stain. The tender shouted something back to the cook in a language Max didn't understand. From the sound of the man's voice Max thought that he wanted to get Max out of there and quickly.
<br />
"I see...that I'm not welcome here...I'll take my burger and water to go." He said as he tossed a few dollars onto the counter for the meal.
<br />
"That would be wise bub. We don't take to kindly to soldier boys around here." Said the tender as he spit onto the floor.
<br />
"I see...well thanks for the food." Max said as he took his burger and water heading out of the bar.
<br />

<br />
Max muttered under his breath as he made his way up the street. "No respect, some people." Shaking his head in disbelief he sat there on a bench drinking his water and eating his burger while watching the people go by. At the back of his mind he thought it quite odd that none of the people here were gearing up for war, but then again he wasn't the poor fool in charge of telling them. He sat there for a few more moments before checking his watch. It was now 21:00. As he got to his feet he decided to head over to the main administration wing of the station for his meeting with Mazuko.
<br />
Commander Sterling sighed and chuckled before commenting quietly. "Well, here goes nothing." With that he headed off for his meeting.<br />_________________<br />~Die</span><span class="gensmall"><br /><br />Last edited by sergio on Fri Mar 10, 2006 1:02 am; edited 1 time in total</span></td>
